<docs>
	<doc for="RefreshEventHandler">
		<summary>
			<para> Represents the method that handles the <see cref="System.ComponentModel.TypeDescriptor.Refreshed"/> event
 raised when a <see cref="System.Type"/> or component is changed during design time.</para>
		</summary>
		<param name="e">A <see cref="System.ComponentModel.RefreshEventArgs"/> that contains the component or <see cref="System.Type"/> that changed.</param>
		<remarks>
			<para>When you create a <see cref="System.ComponentModel.RefreshEventHandler"/> delegate, you
 identify the method that will handle the event. To associate the event with your
 event handler, add an instance of the delegate to the event. The
 event handler is called whenever the event occurs, unless you remove the
 delegate. For more information about event handler delegates, see <see topic="cpconEventsDelegates"/>.</para>
		</remarks>
		<example>
			<para>The following sample demonstrates how to use a
 <see cref="System.ComponentModel.RefreshEventHandler"/> delegate to handle the
 <see cref="System.ComponentModel.TypeDescriptor.Refreshed"/> event when a type or
 component changes. In the code, the <c>OnRefreshed</c> event handles the event and displays the component
 being changed.</para>
			<para>The code assumes that a <c>TextBox</c> control is already sited on
the form.</para>
			<codelink SampleID="RefreshEventHandler" SnippetID="1"/>
		</example>
		<seealso cref="System.ComponentModel.RefreshEventArgs"/>
		<seealso cref="System.ComponentModel.TypeDescriptor"/>
		<seealso cref="System.ComponentModel.TypeDescriptor.Refresh"/>
	</doc>
</docs>
